{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fogler_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532592/1921013001/0828.xml":{"full_text":"Rail Workers\nDeclare War\nOn Wage Cuts\nHead? of Trainmen. Engi?\nneers and Conductors Say\nReports of Lower Prices\nAre False Propaganda\nAssail Legality of Move\nLee Holds Trade Depres\nsion Brought About Solely\nto Excuse Pav Reduction\nCLEVELAND. Jan. 29.?Heads of three\nbig railroad brotherhoods, in formal\nstatement? here to-night, said the rail- j\nroad men of the country \"will not\npeaceably submit\" to the wage reduc?\ntions which Chicago dispatches say\nthe roads will seek from the Unite?! j\nStates Railway Labor Board in a peti-\ntion to be presented Monday.\nW. G. Lee, president of the Brother?\nhood of Railroad Trainmen; W. S.\nCarter, president of the Brotherhood\nof Locomotive Firemen and Enginenien,\nand L. E. Sheppard, president of the\nOrder of Railway Conductors, made\nthis declaration in formal statements.\nA similar declaration was made Thurs?\nday by Warren S. Stone, grand chief\nof the Brotherhood of Locomotive En?\ngineers.\nAll the Brotherhood executives dc- j\nclare that reports of decreases In the l\ncost of living are not borne out by j\nactual conditions, but are the result of j\npropoganda; that the wages of railway j\nemployees did not increase as much,\n:is did the cost of living or as much,\nr.nd that railway men are not now re?\nceiving es high a standard of vages\nas are paid in many other industries.\nMr. Lee asserted that, in his opinion,\n\"some, if not the greater portion, of\nthe business depression has been\nbrought about solely for the purpose\nof prejudicing the public in the inter?\nest, of a reduction in wages generally.''\nMr. Carter declared that \"notwith?\nstanding all the wage increases mad?'\neither by the Railroad Administration\nor the Labor Board it can be shown\nthat because of the great increase in\nthe efficiency of railroad employees\nthere has been no practical increase\nin wage costs compared with product.\"\nMr. Sheppard asserted that \"to a?d\nmit that in this country of ours it is\nnecessary to make an onslaught on\nlabor at this time, after all tne coun?\ntry has d me tof Lie railroads, is abso?\nlutely un-Amertcai4..\"\nMessrs. Lee, Carter and Sheppard\nalso pointed out that the railway em?\nployee is a piece worker, laid olf and\nnot paid when railroad traffic is light.\nThey also took the positi n ti at before\nthe railroads could present req lests\nfor wage red ictions to the be ird they\nwould first have to present them t?\nthe' men and, ncgotiat:<?ns failing\nAere. i;. n appeal to the board.\nHalf Billion Pay Slash\nPlanned by Railroads\n\nConimlttee Considers Three\nWays to Effect Annual Sav?\ning Already Determined Upon\nSpecial Dispatch to The Tribune\nCHICAGO, -Ian. 29.?Agreed that half\nbillion dollars must be cut from the\noperating expanses of American rail?\nroads, but undecided as tr? the best\nway of accomplishing that economy,\nthe labor committee of the American\nAssociation of Railway Executives *o\nday continued discussion of their plan\nto reduce the wages of railroad em?\nployees throughout the country in\norder to assure the roads a 6 per cent\nrevenue.\nY\\\\ \\V. Attrrbury, vice-president of\nthe Pennsylvania lines and chairman\n?,'f the committee, and a half dozen\ni-fcilr ad presidents who arc associated\nwith him, declined to reveal the de?\ntails of the plan, the progress already\nmade or thi probable decisions. The\ncommittee met behind locked doors at\nthe Blackstone Hotel.\nIt was generally understood, how?\never, that the executives agree in be?\nlieving t5*at railroad labor must give\nup, in e way or another, between\nS40P,0(iO.Oao and $5Q0 QOO 000 a year if\nthe railroads art? to earn the 6 per\ncent retcrn guaranteed them by the\nFederal transportation set.\nThree Courses Open\nThree ways >i accomplishing this cut\nin wages have been suggested, it is\nsaid. They are:\nInauguration of a publicity campaign\nto win public support of the retrench?\nment program, this campaign to in?\nclude advertising f the \"secret diplom\nac. which is ;?liv 4 to have been be?\nhind th Ada'jnson law and subsequent\nrailway wage awards. Advocates of\nthis plan that wages could be\nreduced without difficulty once the\npublic ha?! been convinced of the jus\ntic? of such a move.\nAn imm.-d?ate show-down to brins:\nthe case before the United St-.tes Rail?\nway Lahor Wage Board. Under this\nplan the railway brotherhoods would\nbe asked to consent to a wage cut. In\nevent of a refusal the ca?e could then\nbe taken straight to the Federal board\nas an appeal for emergency relief. It\nwas in this way that the brotherhoods\ninitiated the proceedings which led to\na general wage increase last year.\n_ Uncompromising war with labor in\nthe old-fashioned manner. Such a\nmove would be started bv suspending\nhigh-priced men and curtailing activi?\nties. Then jobs would be filled with\n?heap recruits from the growing ranks\nof unemployed.\nFew Favor Labor War\nthe first and second ??Ians, it is said,\nare more in favor than the third,\nwhich has few supporter--. That one\npian or another will be adopted is con\nMdered certain, for every member of\nthe conference is said to be convinced\nthat a reduction at -vapen A necessary.\nrrom the executive?' viewpoint a cut\nof approximately ???,000,000 a year\n!.n. operating expenses ?a essential.\nAbiogation of the national shop agree?\nments, over which labor chiefs and\nrailroad heads are now fighting before\nthe Railroad ?Labor Board, will eliminate\nbjtween *100,000,<H>0 and $150,000000\nof present expeles, it i, estimated.\nThe railroad head? say the remainder\n?a be ?eliminated only by reducing\n?j?_! c?rnmi\"c? k? not the right to\ndec-de for the American Association\nof Railway Executives. The associa-\n?on i* likely, however, to approve the\ncommittee's findings.\njJfTft?!?.*1 th1 ??id to\n\"rough to-morrow. A decision prob\n?b!y w,ll be reached by Monday, it is\nfttimaniii Pro? lairm Si#-gr\nOn Right Back of UnieMer\nVJhSSA.{an. 2? (Jewish Telegraphic\nAdtnry). The Rumanian government\nbaa declared the right bt.nk of the\nDniester River to be in a state of siese\nand has prohibited all traffic in that\nrtigton, according to a Bochar ?at din\npatch received here to-day.\nJewish emigration, which was ouit?\na-Bfid?rab!e at that point, has b?-n\n?wmpletely lispended.\nCanfield's Old Place\nIs Damaged by Fire\nFamous $100,000 \"Ceiling in\nFormer Fashionable Gambling\nPalace Is Destroyed\nFire yesterday morning swept the\nbasement and nrsl and second floors\nof the building at 5 East Forty-fourth\nStreet, occupied years ago by the gam?\nbling establishment of Richard Can\ntield, and caused a loss estimated a1\n?50.000.\nA ceiling which at the time it was\ninstalled was said to have cost $100,\n000, was destroyed by the flames. The\ncause of the lire has not been deter?\nmined.\nThe first and second floors of the\nbuilding were occupied by Charles E.\nBrickley <!fc Co. The bead of that\nbrokerage firm, a former Harvard foot?\nball star, had moved only a week ago\nfrom Delmonico's, in the building two\ndoors away. The tailoring shop of\nIverson Hen.age, at 7 East Forty\nfourth Street, was damaged to the ex?\ntent of $5,000, when the lire spread\nthrough a pipe.\nHeavy mahogany doors, apparently\ndesigned by Canfield to resist a possible\ninvasion by the police, almost caused\n?.-.?realer damage by the flames. It was\nnecessary for firemen to use battering\nrams to got at the blaze.\n-m ?m\nAlbany Officials\nj\nUrge Arbitration\nTo End Car Strike\nTrolley Traffic in Five Up?\nstate Cities at Complete\nStaiidsti]],With Both Sides\nRefusing to. Yield a Point\nSpecial Dispatch to The Tribu?'\nALBANY, Jan. 29.?The people of\nAlbany either walked or rode in jit?\nneys to-day. The strike of the 1,200\nemployees of the United Traction\nCompany, which serves this and sur?\nrounding cities, started at midnight\nlast night and no signs of a settlement\nare in sight.\nA committee of city officials held a\nconference to-night with representa?\ntives of both sides in an effort to bring\nthe men and company together in an\narbitration agreement. It failed to\neffect a settltment.\nThe strike is the result of a cut in\npay from 60 to 45 cents an hour. The\nmen claim that the agreement to pay\n60 cents was to last until next July.\niK ouic?aiS of the company insist thai\n.t was contingent on a 10-cent fare\nbeing grained by the Public Service\nCommi -si.?n.\nA seven-cent fare has been in effect\nhere for a year or more. T.e company\nrecently applied to the Public Service\nCommission for permission to charge\n10 cents. Under the decision of the\ncommission last week, the company\nwas allowed to increase its fare in\nAlbany to eight cents, while the fare in\nTroy was reduced to six cents and that\nin Rensselaer to five cents. The company\nimmedi ite'y announced the reduction\nin pay to become operative the end of\nthis month.\nThe reason for the reduction of fare\nin Troy and Rensselaer was because of\nfranchise restrictions, those cities re?\nfusing to waive their contract rights.\nThey had stt. od for an incre-rsed fare,\nnut a time limit, expiring this month,\nw .a placed on it.\nAlbanians claim that a seven-cent fre\nis sufficient to, give the men in this\ncity the pay they are now getting, and\nthat the necessity for a 10 cent fare\nwas to enable the company to carry\nalong its Trey ano. Rensselaer lines. For\nt'a: reason, Mayor Watt made the\nthreat to-day to start an action in the\ncourts to dissolve the merger of the\nTroy and Albany campa nies, which\nmake up the United Traction Company.\nNo trouble has accompanied the\nstrike, although the police have had\nsome difficulty in handling the in?\ncreased automobile traf\".::. Everybody\nwho owns an automobile got it out of\nwinter at rage and many began carry?\ning passengers at 10 cents a trip early\nthis morning. Many big stores used\ntrucks to cet their employees to work.\nThe opinion of the people appears to\nbe equally dividid en the strike ques?\ntion is t o drastic at this time, with the\ndeclare that the cut in wages had to\ncom?j if the lines were to be kept in\noperation, while the men's sympathiz?\ners believe that the 25 por cent reduc?\ntion is too drastic at th:'s time with the\ncost of living still far above normal.\nPastor Dives Beneath Ice\nTo Save Children 1 Dies\nPulmotor Fails to Resuscitate\nFive-Year-Old Daughter of\nRev. D. S. Ajrnew\nThe Rev. David S. Acnew, rector of\nSt. George's Episcopal Church, in East\n219th Street, the Bronx, dived into a\nfissur? in the ice of the Bronx River\nyesterday and swam ashore with his\ndaughter, Eleanor, five years old, and\nhis son, David, six, who had fallen\ninto the water. It was in-possible to\nrevive the girl, although a pulmotor\nwhs used.\nThe clergyman was at his home. CGI\nEast 2l9ih Street, when he heaid cries\nfrom the river, 200 feet away, where\nhis children were playing with others\nHe ran to the shore. The ice had\nbroken under the children's weight,\nprecipitating David and Eleanor into\nthe water and almost engulfing two\nthers. David was clinging to the ice\na,t the erige of the break. Eleanor was\nnot to be seen.\nThe children pointed out the spot\nwhere she had been swept under the\nice. and the clergyman plunged into the\nwater and swam beneath the ice untii\nhe found her. As soon as he had\nbrought ly ashore he returned fot\nDavid, a, car. ied them both to his\nhome. An ambulance was called, but\n'?a?-;? n s pr tracted efforts with\nthe pulmotor were of no avail to bring\nthe girl back to life.\nGirl Disappears After\nTrip Here From Cuba\nParents Notify Jersey City Po?\nlice She Is Missing Since\nDecember 22\nJersey City police aro mystified by\nthe disappearance of Miss Mirtha E.\nCrowell, daughter of Mr, and Mrs.\nWilliam Crowell. of 16 Madison Ave?\nnue, that city. The missing girl has\n*ot been heard from since December\n22, although her parents failed to re?\nport thr; case uniil Friday night.\nMiss Crowell had visited her sister,\nMrs. C. K. Leblanc, at Santiago, Cuba,\nand ?ailed for home on December 18.\nMrs. Leblanc later was notified by\ncable from her niece that she had ar?\nrived safely on December 22. Because\nof the uncertainty of the time she was\nto leav? Cuba, no member of the fam\ni'y was at the boat to meet the girl\nwhen she reached New York and noth?\ning hau been heard from her since.\nInquiry shows that Miss Crowell was\nn passenger on the steamship Carillo j\nof the United Fruit Company, She Ik\ntwenty-one years old, five fi et four i\nincb?S tall, na? blue eye? anu brown\nhair, and a? far as t he family know?\nwax not involved in any love affair.\nOld yr>ti lo?*? ?mi? ?rulnnlitr krxtpanl??? I\nTry j^,at n;i?l Kr,?.ai<1 u<1 In The Tribun?\n1'ifjlln li<ir.?u,*Ii Ailvt.\nMON I C\nA STORE OF INDIVIDUAL SHOPS\nFIFTH AVENUE, 37th and 38th STS? NEW YORK I\nAnnouncing the Debut of a New Model in the\nBramley Group of Youthful Fashions\nMISSES'\n\n(Registration applied for)\nOF WOOL JERSEY\nExclusive with Franklin Simon Co,\n35.00\nPRESERVING the \"family\ncharacteristics\" of the two\npiece Bramley Dress first in?\ntroduced to youthful wearers\nby Franklin Simon Co., the\n._, one-piece Bramley Dress dis\nffl? plays individual charm that\nijfj? bids fair to eclipse its prede\ncessor in Fashion's favor.\nHenna, Gray, Wren Tan or Navy Blue with Oyster\nWhite Linen Collar and Cuffs Piped to Match;\nKnee-Length, Hand-Sewed Hem\nSIZES 14 to 20 YEARS\nMISSES* GOWK SHOP? Second Floor\nFOR WOMEN\nShaggy Wool Cape\nA NEW KNITTED FABRIC\nExclusive with Franklin Simon Co.\nThe Success of the Resort\nSeason on the Continent\nand in America\n50.\n00\nAMONG the distinguished foreign\ni fashions to establish their vogue\nin America this season is the shaggy\nwool cape, whose favor now reaches\nthe sunshine resorts, to return again to\nthe metropolis and Northern and\nEastern resorts when their suns